candidateAnswer:
Yes – heavy work such as fetching and sorting Core Data records should not be done in a SwiftUI view’s initializer. The initializer is called every time the view is recreated, which can happen frequently, and doing expensive work there can cause performance problems and UI lag.

A better approach is to move the data‑loading logic out of the view and into a separate source of truth, typically an `ObservableObject` (a view model) or a `@FetchRequest`/`NSFetchedResultsController` that is owned by the view hierarchy.

**Common patterns**
1. **`@FetchRequest` with sort descriptors** – For simple read‑only scenarios you can let SwiftUI fetch the data for you:
   ```swift
   struct MyListView: View {
       @FetchRequest(
           entity: Item.entity(),
           sortDescriptors: [NSSortDescriptor(keyPath: \Item.name, ascending: true)],
           animation: .default
       ) private var items: FetchedResults<Item>

       var body: some View { List(items) { … } }
   }
   ```
   The fetch request is evaluated lazily and only when the view appears, and SwiftUI automatically updates the UI when the underlying data changes.

2. **View‑model (`ObservableObject`)** – When you need more control (e.g., custom predicates, batch processing, or asynchronous work), create a dedicated view‑model:
   ```swift
   class MyListViewModel: ObservableObject {
       @Published var items: [Item] = []
       private let context: NSManagedObjectContext

       init(context: NSManagedObjectContext = PersistenceController.shared.container.viewContext) {
           self.context = context
           loadItems()
       }

       func loadItems() {
           let request: NSFetchRequest<Item> = Item.fetchRequest()
           request.sortDescriptors = [NSSortDescriptor(keyPath: \Item.name, ascending: true)]
           // Perform on a background queue if the fetch could be expensive
           context.perform {
               do {
                   let result = try self.context.fetch(request)
                   DispatchQueue.main.async { self.items = result }
               } catch {
                   // handle error
               }
           }
       }
   }
   ```
   In the view you instantiate the model once with `@StateObject` so the fetch runs only once:
   ```swift
   struct MyListView: View {
       @StateObject private var viewModel = MyListViewModel()
       var body: some View { List(viewModel.items) { … } }
   }
   ```

3. **`task` / `onAppear`** – If you prefer to keep the view‑model simple and run the fetch lazily, you can trigger the work when the view appears:
   ```swift
   struct MyListView: View {
       @State private var items: [Item] = []

       var body: some View {
           List(items) { … }
               .task { await loadItems() }
       }

       func loadItems() async {
           let request: NSFetchRequest<Item> = Item.fetchRequest()
           request.sortDescriptors = [NSSortDescriptor(keyPath: \Item.name, ascending: true)]
           do {
               let result = try PersistenceController.shared.container.viewContext.fetch(request)
               items = result
           } catch {
               // handle error
           }
       }
   }
   ```
   The `task` modifier runs once when the view first appears, keeping the initializer lightweight.

**Why this matters**
- **Performance** – Fetching on the main thread in an initializer can block UI updates. Moving the work to a background queue or to SwiftUI‑managed fetches avoids jank.
- **Lifecycle** – SwiftUI may recreate a view many times (e.g., after state changes). Doing the fetch in `init` would repeat the work unnecessarily. Using `@StateObject` or `@FetchRequest` guarantees the work runs only when the underlying object is created, not on every view recomposition.
- **Testability** – Encapsulating the logic in a view‑model makes it easier to unit‑test the data‑loading code.

**Bottom line**: Replace the Core Data fetch and sort in the view initializer with either a `@FetchRequest` that includes the appropriate `sortDescriptors`, or a dedicated `ObservableObject` (or async `task`/`onAppear`) that performs the fetch once, preferably off the main thread. This keeps the view’s initializer cheap and ensures smooth UI performance.

