In modern Swift you should use the Swift concurrency model and the MainActor. After the background `await` call finishes, switch to the main actor before touching any UI state:

```swift
@MainActor
class ViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var text = ""

    func loadData() async {
        // Run the network request off the main thread (URLSession is already async)
        let (data, _) = try? await URLSession.shared.data(from: url)
        // Switch back to the main actor to update UI‑bound state
        await MainActor.run {
            self.text = String(data: data, encoding: .utf8) ?? ""
        }
    }
}
```

* `await MainActor.run { … }` guarantees the closure executes on the main thread.
* Alternatively, you can mark the whole function that updates UI with `@MainActor`, e.g. `@MainActor func updateUI(with:)` and call it from the background task.
* If you’re still using older APIs, `DispatchQueue.main.async { … }` works, but `MainActor` is the preferred, type‑safe way in Swift 5.5+.

So the modern, concurrency‑first approach is to await the network call and then use `await MainActor.run { … }` (or an `@MainActor`‑annotated function) to ensure UI updates happen on the main thread.

