Use `onChange` with either the 0-parameter or 2-parameter variant:

```swift
// 0-parameter: just react
.onChange(of: searchText) {
    performSearch()
}

// 2-parameter: access old and new
.onChange(of: searchText) { oldValue, newValue in
    if newValue.count > oldValue.count { showSuggestions() }
}
```

candidateAnswer:
To react to a search field’s value changes in SwiftUI, attach the .onChange(of:perform:) modifier to the view that holds the @State (or @Binding) representing the search text. The modifier’s closure receives the new value as its sole argument. For example:

@State private var query = ""
var body: some View {
    TextField("Search", text: $query)
        .onChange(of: query) { newValue in
            // run code whenever the search field changes
            print(newValue)
        }
}

If you also need the previous value, use the iOS 17+/macOS 14+ overload .onChange(of:initial:perform:) which provides both the new and old values to the closure: .onChange(of: query, initial: false) { newValue, oldValue in … }.

Thus, the change callback receives the new value (and, with the newer overload, also the old value).

