Use a scalable size value (e.g., @ScaledMetric or UIFontMetrics) to define your base point size, then apply that size to a SwiftUI Font. For example:

@ScaledMetric var customSize: CGFloat = 20   // base size larger than body
var body: some View {
    Text("Hello")
        .font(.system(size: customSize))
}

The @ScaledMetric wrapper automatically adjusts the value according to the user’s Dynamic Type settings, giving you a custom point size that still respects text‑size preferences. (Alternatively, you can use UIFontMetrics to scale a UIFont and convert it to Font with Font(scaledUIFont).)

