Use `@ViewBuilder`:

```swift
@ViewBuilder
func makeView(isRed: Bool) -> some View {
    if isRed {
        Text("Red").foregroundStyle(.red)
    } else {
        Text("Blue").foregroundStyle(.blue)
    }
}
```

Or extract into a separate `View` struct.

candidateAnswer:
In SwiftUI, a function that builds views should return an opaque view type (`some View`) and be marked with `@ViewBuilder` (or rely on SwiftUI’s implicit view builder). This lets you return different concrete view types in different branches while the compiler treats them as the same generic `some View`. If you truly need to return unrelated types that are not views, you can erase them to `AnyView`, but this incurs a performance cost and should be avoided when possible. Example:

```swift
@ViewBuilder
func makeView(condition: Bool) -> some View {
    if condition {
        Text("Hello")          // returns Text
    } else {
        Image(systemName: "star") // returns Image
    }
}
```

Both branches return views, so the function’s opaque `some View` satisfies the type system. If you need to return, say, a `View` and a `UIViewControllerRepresentable`, you can still use `some View` because both conform to `View`; otherwise, wrap each branch in `AnyView` to unify the return type.

