    await MainActor.run { self.items = data }
}
```

Or mark the property/class as `@MainActor` so updates happen automatically.

Use an `actor`:

```swift
actor Cache {
    private var store: [String: Data] = [:]

    func get(_ key: String) -> Data? { store[key] }
    func set(_ key: String, data: Data) { store[key] = data }
}
```

Actors provide compile-time data race protection.

candidateAnswer:
Make the cache thread‑safe by encapsulating it in an actor (or protecting it with a lock/serial queue). An actor ensures that only one task can execute its methods at a time, so concurrent reads and writes are automatically serialized. Example:

actor Cache<Key: Hashable, Value> {
    private var storage = [Key: Value]()
    func value(for key: Key) -> Value? { storage[key] }
    func set(_ value: Value, for key: Key) { storage[key] = value }
    func removeValue(for key: Key) { storage.removeValue(forKey: key) }
}

If you prefer a lock‑based approach, use an NSLock, os_unfair_lock, or a serial DispatchQueue with barrier for writes and sync for reads.

